@node "ChangeSIG"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                ChangeSIG -- Changes the users' special interest group.

   SYNOPSIS
                ChangeSIG <SIG Tag> [MSG]

   FUNCTION
                Changes the online users' special interest group. This
                function affects the "group" of message areas that the
                user has access to.

                See the Chapter "Special Interest Groups" for more
                information on how they work.

                Both the current file and message special interest groups
                will be affected if there are file and message areas
                attached to the SIG. This feature can be disabled by
                specifying the 'MSG' keyword, which will affect only the
                user's message area SIG setting.

   INPUTS
                SIG Tag  - Eight character or less "TAG" identifying the
                           special interest group.

                MSG      - Affect only the users' message SIG setting.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- New SIG set, or FILE argument was specified.
                 2 -- User may not access SIG
                 5 -- Bad arguments
                10 -- SIG does not exist
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

        @{"GetSIG" link "GetSIG"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "ChangeMsgArea"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                ChangeMsgArea -- Changes the users' current message area.

   SYNOPSIS
                ChangeMsgArea <Area Number> [ALL]

   FUNCTION
                Changes the online users' current message area. This setting
                applies to most of the Message ARexx functions- this
                area will be used as a default.

                Various Control Codes will use this setting, see numbers
                2030 and greater.

                Access to the area may be refused for any of these reasons:
                        - Access Level too low or too high according to
                          the definition for the area in Prefs/MsgConfig.
                        - User may be too young as defined in the area
                          definition within Prefs/MsgConfig. Please note:
                          Those with Age "0", meaning undefined will be
                          able to access this area.
                        - User may be the wrong gender to access this
                          area, as defined in the area definition. Those
                          with Gender "UNKNOWN" will be able to access
                          this area regardless.
                        - User does not have ACCESS flag defined in
                          the applicable area range in Prefs/Templates.
                        - Area is not within the definition of the current
                          Special Interest Group, unless the "ALL" argument
                          is specified.


   INPUTS
                Area Number - the number of the area to change to.

                ALL         - do not check whether the area is defined in
                              the special interest groups.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- Message area set
                 2 -- User may not access area
                 5 -- Bad arguments
                10 -- Message area does not exist
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** Sets the user's message area to number 500
                */

                Write '"Old Message Area: %2030| - %2031|\n"'

                GetMsgArea '500' 'Name'
                if RC = 0 then do
                        Write '"Changing to 'RESULT'...\n"'

                        /* Ignore SIG settings */

                        ChangeMsgArea 500 'ALL'

                        select
                                when RC = 0 then do
                                        Write '"New Message Area: %2030| - %2031|\n"'
                                        end

                                when RC = 2 then do
                                        Write '"You do not have access to this area!\n"'
                                        end
                                end

                        end
                else
                        Write '"Message Area 500 does not exist!\n"'

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

        @{"GetMsgArea" link "GetMsgArea"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "CheckWaitingMail"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                CheckWaitingMail -- Returns information about mail waiting for
                                    online user

   SYNOPSIS
                CheckWaitingMail <Waiting Mail Number> <AREA|NUMBER>

   FUNCTION
                Returns information about an item of waiting mail for the
                online user. Waiting mail is numbered from one upwards and
                is stored in the file "USER:User_Name/WaitingMail.Dat"
                where USER: is the path set in the System Preferences
                program.

                For each piece of waiting mail, two fields are stored,
                the area number the message belongs to, and the message
                number this item refers to.

   INPUTS
                Waiting Mail Number - The ordinal number of the waiting
                                      mail data to retrieve.
                                      
                AREA                - Return the area number this message
                                      belongs to.

                NUMBER              - Return the message number of the
                                      waiting mail.

   RESULT

   RC
                0  -- Data requested returned
                5  -- No more waiting mail

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** Outputs a simple list of waiting mail
                */

                fin = 0
                num = 1

                do until fin = 1
                        CheckWaitingMail num 'Area'
                        if RC = 0 then do
                                WMArea = RESULT

                                CheckWaitingMail num 'Number'
                                if RC = 0 then do
                                        WMNum = RESULT

                                        Write '"Message Waiting:"'
                                        Write '"'Area 'WMArea' - "'
                                        Write '"'Number 'WMNum'\n"'

                                        num = num + 1
                                        end
                                else
                                        fin = 1
                                end
                        else
                                fin = 1
                        end

                if num = 1 then Write '"No mail waiting!\n"'

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

        @{"DeleteWaitingMail" link "DeleteWaitingMail"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "ConvertMsgDate"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                ConvertMsgDate -- Converts a date string into Zeus date format.

   SYNOPSIS
                ConvertMsgDate <Date String> 

   FUNCTION
                Converts a date in format "DD-MMM-YY HH:MM:SS" into Zeus time
                format (number of seconds since 1st January 1978).

                The time string may be omitted if desired.

   INPUTS
                Date String -- Date to Convert.

   RESULT
                Date in Zeus time format.

   RC
                 0 -- Data requested returned
                 5 -- Invalid date
                10 -- Bad arguments

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** Converts a few example date strings.
                */

                Date = '19-Sep-95 20:30:59'
                Call ConvDate
                Date = '04-Apr-91 10:12:20'
                Call ConvDate
                Date = '21-Jun-96"'
                Call ConvDate
                Date = '21-Brian-96 99:99:99"'
                Call ConvDate

                exit

                ConvDate:
                        ConvertMsgDate '"'Date'"'
                        if RC = 0 then Write '"'Date' is 'RESULT' seconds from Jan 1, 1970\n"'
                        if RC = 5 then Write '"'Date' is an invalid date!\n"'
                        Return

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                @{"Strftime" link "Strftime"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "DeleteMsgFilter"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                DeleteMsgFilter -- Deactivates message filter used by LoadMsg.

   SYNOPSIS
                DeleteMsgFilter

   FUNCTION
                Cancels any message filter settings, as used by
                rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg. This will ensure that all messages
                will be returned from LoadMsg, and no matching will take
                place.

                This function should be used before a message filter is
                created by calls to rexxMsgCommands/SetMsgFilter.

   INPUTS
                None.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- Filter removed
                20 -- Fatal error

   SEE ALSO
                @{"SetMsgFilter" link "SetMsgFilter"} @{"LoadMsg" link "LoadMsg"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "DeleteWaitingMail"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                DeleteWaitingMail -- Deletes current user's waiting mail file.

   SYNOPSIS
                DeleteWaitingMail

   FUNCTION
                Deletes the waiting mail data for the online user. The
                physical file "USER:User_Name/WaitingMail.Dat" is removed
                from the file system, and any calls to CheckWaitingMail
                will not return information until new messages are saved
                addressed to the online user.

   INPUTS
                None.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- Waiting mail deleted
                 5 -- No waiting mail file to delete
                10 -- Could not delete file

   SEE ALSO
                @{"CheckWaitingMail" link "CheckWaitingMail"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "DisplayMsg"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                DisplayMsg -- Outputs the current message text to the user.

   SYNOPSIS
                DisplayMsg [PAGE <Output String>]

   FUNCTION
                Outputs the message text currently in memory to the user.
                This function requires that rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg has been
                called and returned 0 indicating that the message was
                successfully read.

                DisplayMsg performs various processing on the text,
                depending upon the message area configuration for the
                message currently loaded.

                The following flags will affect DisplayMsg:

                      Kludges    - If set, FidoNet kludges will be output.
                                   A kludge is a line beginning with the
                                   CTRL-A (0x01) character.

                       SeenBys    - If set, FidoNet seen-by lines will be
                                   output. A seen-by is a line beginning
                                   with the text "SEEN-BY: ".

                      Paths      - If set, FidoNet path lines will be
                                   output. A path is a line beginning with
                                   the text "PATH: ".

                      AnsiBase   - If set, lines will not be highlighted,
                                   and text styles will not be displayed.

                      TextStyles - If set, Text Styles will be output to
                                   the screen.
                     

   INPUTS
                PAGE - String to output after a page of text has been
                       displayed and more has been requested.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- Displayed message text
                10 -- No message currently loaded
                20 -- Fatal error
                
   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "DumpMsgHdr"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                DumpMsgHdr -- Outputs message information to an FTSC-1
                              compatible message.

   SYNOPSIS
                DumpMsgHdr [AREA <Area Number>] [MSG <Message Number>]
                                          [FILENAME <Output File>] [APPEND]

   FUNCTION
                Outputs a message header an FTSC-1 compatible FidoNet
                message file.

                This function is especially useful for text editors that
                extract message header information when replying to a
                message. AED is a case in point, and is supplied on
                Zeus Distribution Disk 4 (AED138.lha)

                This function will take the current loaded message as it's
                default arguments for AREA and MSG if run from an online
                script. FILENAME will also default to "t:MsgHdr.<Line>".

   INPUTS
                AREA     - Area number of message.
                MSG      - Message number of message.
                FILENAME - Output file
                APPEND   - Append instead of overwriting output file.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- Message header was dumped
                 2 -- Cannot open output file
                 5 -- Cannot load message
                10 -- Bad arguments

   EXAMPLE
                ---Prefs/Editors->AED->Edit Scripts---

                #MSG

                /** Dump Message Header to T:Out.<Line> for use with AED **/

                DumpMsgHdr 'FILENAME' 't:out.'Line
                if RC = 0 then
                        CLIDoor '"AEd %70| %71| t:MsgText.'Line' t:out.'Line :: %125|%313|"'
                else
                        CLIDoor '"AEd %70| %71| t:MsgText.'Line' :: :: %125|%313|"'

                --------------------------------------

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/DumpMsgText, rexxMsgCommands/ImportMsgHdr

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "DumpMsgText"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                DumpMsgText -- Outputs message text to a file.

   SYNOPSIS
                DumpMsgText [AREA <Area Number>] [MSG <Message Number>]
                                          [FILENAME <Output File>] [APPEND]

   FUNCTION
                This function will output a message text verbatim to
                a specified file.

                If this function is called from an online script, the
                AREA and MSG arguments will default to the current loaded
                message, as read by rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg. The default
                FILENAME will be "t:MsgText.<Line>".

   INPUTS
                AREA     - Area number of message.
                MSG      - Message number to output.
                FILENAME - File to output text to.
                APPEND   - Append to file instead of overwriting.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- Message text was dumped
                 2 -- Cannot open output file
                 5 -- Cannot load message
                10 -- Bad arguments

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** Download the text of the current message
                */

                ExpandCC '"%2030|"'
                MessageNumber = RESULT

                FN = 't:MsgText.'MessageNumber

                DumpMsgText 'FileName' '"'FN'"'
                if RC = 0 then do
                        Download 'DOSFILE' '"'FN'"'
                        end
                else
                        Write '"Error outputting message to disk!\n"'

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/DumpMsgHdr, rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "ChangeEditor"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                ChangeEditor -- Changes the user's current editor setting.

   SYNOPSIS
                ChangeEditor <Editor Number>

   FUNCTION
                Changes the default editor for the online user when writing
                message text and file descriptions.

                ChangeEditor does not check whether the user may use this
                editor, using the configuration defined in Prefs/Editors.
                You must check whether the user may access this editor in
                your script. See the GetEditor function for an example of
                how to do this.

   INPUTS
                Editor Number -- The editor number to set.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- New editor set
                 5 -- Bad arguments
                10 -- Editor does not exist
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** Sets the user's editor to the default
                */

                GetEditor 'Name'
                if RC = 0 then Write '"Current Editor Setting: 'RESULT'\n"'

                ChangeEditor 1
                if RC = 0 then do
                        GetEditor 'Name'
                        Write '"    New Editor Setting: 'RESULT'\n"'
                        end
                else
                        Write '"Could not set users editor!\n"'

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
        GetEditor

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "FreeScanTopics"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                FreeScanTopics -- Returns resources used by ScanTopics to the system.

   SYNOPSIS
                FreeScanTopics

   FUNCTION
                This function should be called after a successful call to
                rexxMsgCommands/ScanTopics.  It will free all memory resources
                that were allocated by this function.

                This function can be called safely multiple times.

   INPUTS
                None.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- Topic data freed
                20 -- Fatal error

   NOTES
                Once this function has been called, topic-related functions
                will be disabled. This applies to rexxMsgCommands/GetTopic
                and rexxMsgCommands/GetTopicThread as well as the Control
                Codes %2080-%2090.

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/ScanTopics

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "FreeMsg"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                FreeMsg -- Returns resources used by LoadMsg to the system.

   SYNOPSIS
                FreeMsg

   FUNCTION
                This function should be called after a successful call to
                rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg. It will free all memory resources
                this command has allocated.

                This function can be called safely multiple times.

   INPUTS
                None.

   RESULT
                None.

   NOTES
                Once this function has been called, all commands and control
                codes relating to the message will be disabled. Calls to
                rexxMsgCommands/DisplayMsg and the use of the Control Codes
                %2010-%2022 will not function.

   RC
                 0 -- Message freed
                20 -- Fatal error

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetArchiver"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetArchiver -- Returns information about an archive type.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetArchiver <Archiver Name|ORDINAL <Archiver Number>>
                                               [NAME|EXTRACT|COMPRESS|RECOG]

   FUNCTION
                This function returns information from the archivers
                configuration as defined in Prefs/Archivers.

                Data can be retrieved by its name, i.e. LHA or by its
                ordinal number, starting from one in the list.

                Data requested is returned in RESULT.

   INPUTS
                Archiver Name  - Retrieve archiver data for <Archiver Name>
                ORDINAL        - Retrieve archiver data by ordinal number
                                 in configuration list.

                NAME           - Return archiver name.
                EXTRACT        - Return command line used to extract an
                                 archive.
                COMPRESS       - Return command line used to compress an
                                 archive.
                RECOG          - Return recognition string for archiver.

   RESULT
                Data requested.

   RC
                0 -- Requested data returned
                5 -- Archiver does not exist

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** Display a list of archivers.
                */

                ClrScr
                NoArc = 0
                i = 1
                Write '"\n[34mArchivers...\n\n"'
                do until NoArc = 1
                        GetArchiver i 'Name'
                        Name = RESULT
                        if RC ~= 0 then NoArc = 1
                        else do
                                GetArchiver Name 'RECOG'
                                Recog = RESULT

                                Name = Left( Name, 30 )
                                Write '" [37m[[36m'i'[37m] [32m'Name' [33m'Recog'\n"'
                                i = i + 1
                                end
                        end

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetEditor"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetEditor -- Returns information about an editor.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetEditor [Editor Number] [NAME|LOW|HIGH|TYPE|TAG]

   FUNCTION
                This function returns information from the editors
                configuration as defined in Prefs/Editors.

                Editors are referenced by their ordinal position
                in the configuration, starting from one.

   INPUTS
                Editor Number  - Return data for the editor at
                                 position <Editor Number> in the
                                 editors configuration.

                NAME           - Return Editor name.
                LOW            - Return lowest access level required to
                                 access this editor.
                HIGH           - Return highest access level required to
                                 access this editor.
                TYPE           - Return line type required to access
                                 this editor. Return values are:

                                 "REMOTE", "LOCAL", "BOTH"

                TAG <TAG>      - Return ARexx script segment used to load
                                 editor in "TAG" mode. The "Msg/WriteMsg"
                                 script uses the "MSG" tag to edit message
                                 texts.

   RESULT
                Data Requested.

   RC
                 0 -- Data requested returned
                 5 -- Bad arguments
                10 -- Editor does not exist

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** List Editors
                */

                ClrScr

                Write '"\n[32mAvailable editors:\n\n"'
                i = 1
                GetUserData 'Access'
                Access = RESULT

                ExpandCC '"%154|"'
                if RESULT = '0' then         Local = 1
                else                        Local = 0

                do forever
                        GetEditor i 'TYPE'
                        if RC ~= 0 then do
                                /** No more editors, exit loop **/
                                break
                                end

                                /** Check user uses correct line type, LOCAL or REMOTE **/

                                if RESULT ~= 'LOCAL' | ( RESULT = 'LOCAL' & Local = 1 ) then do
                                        GetEditor i 'LOW'
                                        Low = RESULT

                                        GetEditor i 'HIGH'
                                        High = RESULT

                                        /** Check user has required access level **/

                                        if Access >= Low & Access <= High then do
                                                GetEditor i 'NAME'
                                                Write '"   User may access: [32m[[37m'i'[32m] [37m'RESULT'\n"'
                                                end
                                        end
                                i = i + 1
                                end
                        end

                /*
                ** Run Editor
                */

                GetEditor 'TAG' 'MSG'
                if RC = 0 then Interpret RESULT

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/ChangeEditor

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetMsgAccess"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetMsgAccess -- Returns information about user's access flags.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetMsgAccess [Area Number] [ACCESS|READ|WRITE|WRITEPVT|PRIVATEREAD|
                           KILLOWN|KILLALL|FILEATTACH|CRASHNETMAIL|SYSOP|MASKEDOUT]

   FUNCTION
                Returns whether a user has a specified access flag turned
                on or off in a particular area.

                GetMsgAccess will return 0 in RC if the flag does not have
                the attribute set on, or 1 if the user may have use the
                specified privelidge.

                Message Attributes are defined in Prefs/Templates, and are
                set according to the access level of the user. However,
                variations from this access scheme may be made in
                Utils/UserEditor.

                Area Number will default to the current message area if
                no argument is supplied.
                
   INPUTS
                Area Number  - Area number to retrieve access flag
                                setting for.

                ACCESS       - May user access this area?
                READ         - May user read messages in this area?
                WRITE        - May user write messages in this area?
                WRITEPVT     - May user write private messages in this area?
                PRIVATEREAD  - May user read private messages in this area?
                KILLOWN      - May user delete messages written by
                               themselves in this area?
                KILLALL      - May user delete any single message in this
                               area?
                FILEATTACH   - May user attach physical files to messages
                               written by them in this area?
                CRASHNETMAIL - May user write crash netmails in this area?
                               This flag only applies in a NetMail area.
                SYSOP        - May user have SysOp privelidges in this
                               area, such as Forwarding Messages?
                MASKEDOUT    - Has user requested not to receive waiting
                               mail in this area?
                PACK         - Has user requested to export this area for
                               offline reading?

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                 0 -- Flag is not set
                 1 -- Flag is set
                 5 -- Message area does not exist
                10 -- Bad arguments
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** List accessible areas for user.
                */

                Options Results
                Parse Arg Line

                i   = 0
                fin = 0

                do until fin = 1
                        GetMsgArea 'Ordinal' '"'i'"' 'Number'
                        if RC = 0 then do
                                Number = RESULT

                                GetMsgArea 'Ordinal' '"'i'"' 'Name'
                                AreaName = RESULT

                                GetMsgAccess '"'i'"' 'Access'
                                if RC = 0 then  Write '"User may not access 'Number' - 'AreaName'\n"' 'NoMore'
                                else                Write '"User may access 'Number' - 'AreaName'\n"' 'NoMore'

                                i = i + 1
                                end
                        else do
                                /* No more areas */
                                fin = 1
                                end
                        end

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetMsgArea"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetMsgArea -- Returns information about a message area definition.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetMsgArea <Message Area Number|ORDINAL <Number>>
                        [NAME|NUMBER|TAGNAME|BASETYPE|MAXMSGS|LOWACC|HIGHACC|
                         ADDRESS|ORIGIN|ORIGINSTR|EXESTR|MBLIB|AGE|GENDER|
                         KLUDGES|PATHS|SEENBYS|PRIVATE|HIASCII|QUOTING|
                         ALIAS|USERDELMSGS|TEXTSTYLES|ANSIBASE]

   FUNCTION
                Returns configuration information about a message area as
                defined in Prefs/MsgConfig.

                Message Areas can be referenced by their "ordinal" number,
                useful for scanning the entire, or part of the list, or
                by their reference number as defined in the configuration.

                This function returns '0' or '1' for flags, or the data
                requested for numbers and strings in RESULT.

   INPUTS
                Message Area Number  - Reference number of area to return
                                       data for.
                ORDINAL <n>          - Return data for the 'n'th message
                                       area in list.

                String Results:

                NAME      - Return descriptive name of area.
                TAGNAME   - Return FidoNet "tagname" of area.
                BASETYPE  - Return information about the network capability
                            of the message base. Possible return values
                            are: "LOCAL", "ECHOMAIL", "NETMAIL", "UUCP" or
                            "PVTUUCP"
                ADDRESS   - FidoNet address of area, not applicable for
                            LOCAL type bases.
                ORIGIN    - Origin number to use in area. This number
                            refers to the position of the origin in the
                            text configuration file
                            "Zeus:Config/Msg/Origins.Cfg"
                ORIGINSTR - Actual origin line string to use in area.
                            If ORIGIN is 0, and a random origin is to be
                            returned, any origin string could be returned
                            by this call.
                EXESTR    - Executable command line called to process
                            the text of messages written in this area.
                EXE       - Ordinal number of executable, as defined in
                            the Executable list box in Prefs/MsgConfig.
                MBLIB     - Message base library used in area.
                GENDER    - Gender restrictions on area, possible return
                            values are: "N/A", "MALE" (only), "FEMALE"
                            (only).


                Number Results:

                NUMBER    - Return message area reference number.
                MAXMSGS   - Return maximum number of messages to store in
                            message base.
                LOWACC    - Minimum "override" access level required to
                            access area. All other access criteria are
                            ignored, including Template definitions.
                HIGHACC   - Maximum "override" access level required to
                            access area. All other access criteria are
                            ignored, including Template definitions.
                AGE       - Minimum age for user to access area.

                Flag Results:

                PRIVATE     - Messages default to private in this area.
                HIASCII     - Allow 8-bit characters in this area. These
                              are prohibited in most FidoNet echoes.
                QUOTING     - Allow quoting when replying to messages in area.
                USERDELMSGS - User may delete messages in area. Overrides
                              Template Definition "KILLOWN"

                KLUDGES, PATHS, SEENBYS, ANSIBASE, TEXTSTYLES
                          - see rexxMsgCommands/DisplayMsg
                


   RESULT
                Data Requested.

   RC
                 0 -- Data requested returned
                 5 -- No such message area
                10 -- Bad arguments

   EXAMPLE
                See "Zeus:Rexx/MsgTxtCfgDump.rexx"

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/DisplayMsg, rexxMsgCommands/SetMsgArea

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetMsgData"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetMsgData -- Returns information about the currently loaded message.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetMsgData [FILEATTACHED|NEXT|PREV]

   FUNCTION
                Returns information about the currently loaded message.
                This function allows you to access through ARexx information
                that is commonly used when traversing the message base.

                This command requires that a successful call to
                rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg has been made (RC = 0).

                Information requested is returned in RESULT.

   INPUTS
                FILEATTACHED  - Does the current message have a file
                                attached to it. Possible return values,
                                0 for false, 1 for true. The names of the
                                attached files are stored in the Subject
                                lines, separated by spaces.

                NEXT          - Return next message number in thread.

                PREV          - Return previous message number in thread.

   RESULT
                Data requested.

   RC
                 0 -- Data requested returned
                10 -- Bad arguments
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE
        /*
        **        Make those nice "Next/Prev" reply keys...
        */
        DoReply:

                GetMsgData 'PREV'
                PrevRes = RESULT
                GetMsgData 'NEXT'
                NextRes = RESULT

                /*
                **        Are there any replies in any direction?
                */
                of PrevRes ~= 0 | NextRes ~= 0 then do
                        Out = ''

                        /*
                        **        Is the original message left?
                        */
                        if PrevRes ~= 0 then do
                                ExtraKeys = '-'
                                Out = '"[36m[[1;33m-[0;36m][37m <- "'
                                end

                        Out = Out||'"[0;37mRead Replies"'

                /*
                **        Is there a reply to this message?
                */
                IF NextRes ~= 0 thend o
                        Out = Out||'" -> [36m[[1;33m+[0;36m][0;37m"'
                        ExtraKeys = ExtraKeys||'+'
                        end

                Write Out 'NoMore'
                end
        Return

        /*
        ** Check if there were some files attached...
        */
        FileAttach:
                GetMsgData 'FileAttached'
                        if RESULT = 1 then do
                                Write '"\n[0;37mThere are file(s) attached to this message. Press ''[31mD[37m'' to Download.\n"' 'NoMore'
                                ExtraKeys = ExtraKeys||'D'
                                end
                Return


   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetMsgInfo"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetMsgInfo -- Returns information from a message.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetMsgInfo [Msg] [SECTION|NUMBER|TEXTLENGTH|FROM|TO|SUBJECT|DATE|
                      ARRIVEDATE|FROMADDRESS|DESTADDRESS|REPLYTO|NEXTREPLY|
                      PRIVATE|RECEIVEANONYMOUS|SENDERANONYMOUS|DELETEUPONRECEIVE|
                      CRASH|HOLD|DIRECT|TEXT]

   FUNCTION
                Returns information about the message passed in 'Msg'.

                If this is an online script, and a successful call to
                rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg has been made (RC = 0), the 'Msg'
                argument can be omitted, and data from the current
                loaded message will be used instead.

   INPUTS
                MSG                - Message to return information from.

                SECTION            - Message base message belongs to.
                NUMBER             - Message reference number in area.
                TEXTLENGTH         - Length in bytes of the message text.
                FROM               - The author of the message.
                TO                 - The addresse of the message.
                SUBJECT            - The topic of the message.
                DATE               - The date the message was written in
                                     Zeus time format.
                ARRIVEDATE         - The date this message arrived on the
                                     system in Zeus time format.
                FROMADDRESS        - FidoNet address this message came from.
                DESTADDRESS        - FidoNet address this message is destined
                                     for (netmail bases only).
                REPLYTO            - Message number this message is a reply
                                     to, or 0 for an original message.
                NEXTREPLY          - Next message number which is a reply
                                     to this message, or 0 for no more
                                     messages in thread.
                TEXT               - Return unformatted message text.
                                     NB: ARexx supports a maximum string length
                                     of 64k, so check this limit is not
                                     exceeded with the 'TEXTLENGTH' argument.

                Flags - these return 0 or 1 in RESULT.

                PRIVATE           - Message is private.
                RECEIVEANONYMOUS  - The receiver should be anonymous to others.
                SENDERANONYMOUS   - The sender should be anonymous to others.
                DELETEUPONRECEIVE - This message should be deleted once read.
                CRASH             - This message should be sent as
                                    crashmail (netmail bases only).
                HOLD              - This message should be sent as
                                    hold mail (netmail bases only).
                DIRECT            - This message should be sent as
                                    direct mail (netmail bases only).


   RESULT
                Data requested returned.

   RC
                 0 -- Data requested returned
                10 -- Bad arguments

   EXAMPLE
                /** Simple Scan **/

                Options Results
                Parse Arg Line 

                fin = 0

                GetPointer 'Low'
                StartPtr = RESULT

                do until fin = 1
                        LoadMsg StartPtr 'NoText'
                        if RC = 0 then do
                                /** Use GetMsgInfo to return data from message */

                                GetMsgInfo 'FROM'
                                From = RESULT
                                From = Left(From,15,' ')

                                GetMsgInfo 'TO'
                                To = RESULT
                                To = Left(To,15,' ')

                                GetMsgInfo 'SUBJECT'
                                Subject = RESULT
                                Subject = Left(Subject,15,' ')

                                OutLine = '[0;31m#%2011%-4ld| [0;36mFr: [37m'From' [36mTo: [37m'To' [36mSb: [37m'Subject
                                SWrite OutLine
                                Write '"\n"' NoMore

                                FreeMsg
                                end
                        else if RC ~= 2 then do
                                FreeMsg
                                end
                        else do
                                fin = 1
                                end

                        CheckInput
                        IF RC ~= 0 THEN fin = 1
                        StartPtr = StartPtr + 1
                        end

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/GetMsgData, rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetMsgPointer"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetMsgPointer -- Returns current users last read message in an area.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetMsgPointer [AREA <Area Number>]

   FUNCTION
                Returns the value set for the last message the user read in
                'AREA'.

                The current area will be used if the 'AREA' argument is
                not specified.

   INPUTS
                AREA    - Area number to retrieve data for.

   RESULT
                Last read message.

   RC
                 0 -- Data requested returned
                 5 -- Area does not exist
                10 -- Could not get pointer
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** Scan areas for last read pointers.
                */

                Options Results
                Parse Arg Line

                JumpMsgArea 'FIRST'
                if RC = 0 then do
                        do forever

                                /* Do this:

                                    ExpandCC '"%2030|"'
                                   GetMsgPointer AREA '"'RESULT'"'

                                   or-
                                */

                                GetMsgPointer
                                Write '"Area %2030| - %2031|, High Pointer 'RESULT'\n"'

                                JumpMsgArea 'NEXT'
                                if RC ~= 0 then exit
                        end

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/GetPointer

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetPointer"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetPointer -- Returns pointer data about an area number.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetPointer [Area Number] [LOW|HIGH|HSBN]

   FUNCTION
                Returns information about the low, high, and highest
                exported messages in the specified area number. The high
                message pointer updates by one every time a message in
                saved in the area.

                Whenever the message base is trimmed, the low message
                number may increase to limit the number of messages that
                area in the area.

   INPUTS
                Area Number - Area to retrieve information for.

                LOW    - Return the lowest message number in the area.
                HIGH   - Return the highest message number in the area.
                HSBN   - Return the highest message by the network in
                         the area.

   RESULT
                Data requested.

   RC
                 0 -- Data requested returned
                 5 -- Bad arguments
                15 -- Could not get area pointers
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** GetPointers
                */

                Options Results
                Parse Arg Line

                i   = 0
                fin = 0

                do until fin = 1
                        GetMsgArea 'Ordinal' '"'i'"' 'Number'
                        if RC = 0 then do
                                Number = RESULT
                                GetMsgArea 'Ordinal' '"'i'"' 'Name'
                                AreaName = RESULT

                                GetPointer Number 'LOW'
                                Low = RESULT

                                GetPointer Number 'HIGH'
                                High = RESULT

                                GetPointer Number 'HSBN'
                                HSBN = RESULT

                                Write '"'Number' - 'Name' Low: 'Low' High: 'High' HSBN: 'HSBN'\n"'
                                if RC ~= 0 then fin = 1

                                i = i + 1
                                end
                        else do
                                /* No more areas */
                                fin = 1
                                end
                        end


   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/SetPointers

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetThread"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetThread -- Returns message number belonging to a thread.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetThread <NEXT|PREV|ORIGINAL>

   FUNCTION
                Returns information about the thread currently being read
                by rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg.

                A thread is one or more messages linked together by topic.
                They are physically linked using the ^MSGID kludge used
                in FidoNet. Each message in a thread can have a previous
                message, a next message and an original message. However,
                the first message in a thread will not have a previous
                reference, and the last message in a thread will not have
                a next reference. The first message in the thread will
                return itself using the "ORIGINAL" flag.

                The message number will be returned in RESULT.

   INPUTS
                NEXT     - Return the next message in the thread.
                PREV     - Return the previous message in the thread.
                ORIGINAL - Return the first message in the thread.

   RESULT
                Message reference number.                

   RC
                 0 -- Data requested returned
                 5 -- No message loaded
                10 -- Bad arguments
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** GetThread.zeus
                */

                Options Results
                Parse Arg Line

                GetPointer 'Low'
                StartPtr = RESULT

                loadfin = 0

                do until loadfin = 1
                        LoadMsg StartPtr 'NOTEXT'
                        if RC = 0 then do

                                Write '"Thread starting at 'StartPtr': "'

                                fin = 0
                                do until fin = 1
                                        GetThread 'NEXT'
                                        if RC = 0 then do
                                                Next = RESULT
                                                if Next ~= '0' then do
                                                        LoadMsg Next 'NOTEXT'
                                                        if RC ~= 0 then fin = 1
                                                        else do
                                                                Write '"'Next' "'
                                                                end
                                                        end
                                                end
                                        end

                                /** This can go on a long time, so give the
                                    option to quit **/

                                 Write '"\n"'
                                if RC = -5 then loadfin = 1

                                StartPtr = StartPtr + 1
                                end
                        else if RC = 2|RC >= 10 then
                                loadfin = 1
                        end

   NOTES
                This command is not related to the "topic" system, which
                uses the GetTopic and GetTopicThread commands.

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/LoadMsg, rexxMsgCommands/GetTopic

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "GetTopic"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                GetTopic -- Makes a topic thread available to GetTopicThread.

   SYNOPSIS
                GetTopic <FIRST|NEXT|LAST|PREVIOUS|NUMBER <Topic Number>>

   FUNCTION
                Activates the rexxMsgCommands/GetTopicThread command. This
                function requires that rexxMsgCommands/ScanTopics has
                been called succesfully (RC = 0).

                The list created by rexxMsgCommands/ScanTopics can be
                traversed in a variety of different ways, FIRST, NEXT, LAST,
                PREVIOUS and directly by ordinal number (starting from 1)

                The Current Topic Subject can be obtained from Control
                Code %2080 after a successful call to
                rexxMsgCommands/GetTopic.

   INPUTS
                FIRST    - Sets rexxMsgCommands/GetTopicThread to point at
                           the first topic in the scanned area.
                LAST     - Point at the last topic in the scanned area.
                NEXT     - Points at the next topic in the scanned area.
                           This argument requires a call to "FIRST" or
                           "LAST" to have been made.
                PREVIOUS - Points at the previous topic in the scanned
                           area. This argument requires a call to "FIRST" or
                           "LAST" to have been made.

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                0   - GetTopicThread may now access Topic.
                5   - No such topic!
                20  - Fatal error.

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** GetTopic
                */

                Options Results
                Parse Arg Line

                do forever
                        ClrScr

                        GetTopic 'NUMBER' top

                        i   = top
                        len = 0
                        fin = 0

                        do while fin = 0
                                Num = right( i, 4, ' ' )

                                Write '"[1;31m'Num' [0;36m[[1;33m%2081%-2ld|[0;36m] [0;37m%2080|\n"' SpecialMore
                                if RC = -3 then do
                                        fin = 1
                                        end

                                GetTopic 'NEXT'
                                if RC ~= 0 then do
                                        last = top + len
                                        fin = 1
                                        end

                                i   = i + 1
                                end
                        end

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/ScanTopics, rexxMsgCommands/FreeScanTopics,
                rexxMsgCommands/GetTopicThread

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "ImportMsgHdr"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                ImportMsgHdr -- Sets up message information passed to WriteMsg from an
                                FTSC-1 compatible message file.

   SYNOPSIS
                ImportMsgHdr [File Name]

   FUNCTION
                This function works in a similar way to
                rexxMsgCommands/SetMsgData- it will copy relevant information
                from an FTSC-1 compatible message file to the structure
                used by rexxMsgCommands/WriteMsg.

                FTSC-1 compatible message files are used by some mail
                processors, the mbstarmsg.library and also various message
                editors, e.g. AEd 1.38.

                This function will copy the following fields, as defined
                in rexxMsgCommands/SetMsgData.

                        FROM, TO, SUBJECT
                        FROMADDRESS, DESTADDRESS
                        REPLYTO

   INPUTS
                File Name

   RESULT
                None.

   RC
                0  - Message data copied.
                2  - Read error in message file.
                5  - Could not open file.
                20 - Fatal error.

   EXAMPLE
                ---Prefs/Editors->AED->Edit Scripts---

                #MSG

                /** Dump Message Header to T:Out.<Line> for use with AED **/

                DumpMsgHdr 'FILENAME' 't:out.'Line
                if RC = 0 then
                        CLIDoor '"AEd %70| %71| t:MsgText.'Line' t:out.'Line :: %125|%313|"'
                else
                        CLIDoor '"AEd %70| %71| t:MsgText.'Line' :: :: %125|%313|"'

                /** Import any changed data back in **/

                ImportMsgHdr '"t:out"'

                --------------------------------------

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO
                rexxMsgCommands/DumpMsgHdr, rexxMsgCommands/DumpMsgText

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "JumpMsgArea"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                JumpMsgArea -- Changes a users current message area by list order.

   SYNOPSIS
                JumpMsgArea <NEXT|PREV|FIRST|LAST> [IGNORESIG]

   FUNCTION

   INPUTS

   RESULT
                Old Message Area

   RC
                 0 -- Message Area Changed
                 5 -- No more message areas
                10 -- Bad arguments
                20 -- Fatal Error

   EXAMPLE
                /*
                ** Scans the message areas
                */

                fin = 0

                Write '"Scanning Message Areas Forwards...\n\n"'

                JumpMsgArea 'FIRST'
                if RC = 0 then do
                        do until fin = 1
                                Write '"%2030|) %2031|\n"'

                                JumpMsgArea 'NEXT'
                                if RC ~= 0 then fin = 1
                                end
                        end

                Write '"\nScanning Message Areas Backwards...\n\n"'

                fin = 0

                JumpMsgArea 'LAST'
                if RC = 0 then do
                        do until fin = 1
                                Write '"%2030|) %2031|\n"'

                                JumpMsgArea 'PREV'
                                if RC ~= 0 then fin = 1
                                end
                        end

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "KillMsg"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                KillMsg -- Deletes the currently loaded message.

   SYNOPSIS
                KillMsg [Message Number] [AREA <Area Number>]

   FUNCTION

   INPUTS

   RESULT

   RC
                 0 -- Message deleted
                 2 -- User may not delete message
                 5 -- Could not delete message
                10 -- Bad arguments/no message loaded
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE
                Number         = '1'
                Area                = '1'

                LoadMsg '"'Number'"' 'Area' '"'Area'"'
                if RC = 0 then do
                        KillMsg
                        Select
                                When RC = 0 then Write '"\n[31mDeleted Message...\n"'

                                When RC = 2 then Write '"\n[31mYou may not delete this message!\n"'

                                When RC = 5 then Write '"\n[31mError Deleting Message...\n"'
                                end 
                        FreeMsg
                        end
                else
                        Write '"Could not load Msg #'Number' in Area #'Area'!\n"'

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "LoadMsg"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                LoadMsg -- Sets the users current message.

   SYNOPSIS
                LoadMsg [Message Number] [AREA <Area Number>] [NOTEXT] [NOFIDOINFO]
                                  [NEXTMSG] [PREVMSG]

   FUNCTION

   INPUTS

   RESULT
                Message Number

   RC
                 0 -- Message loaded
                 1 -- Message did not match filter
                 2 -- Could not load message
                 3 -- User may not read message
                 4 -- Message does no longer exist
                 5 -- Bad arguments
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "MaskMsgArea"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                MaskMsgArea -- Controls masking information for a message area.

   SYNOPSIS
                MaskMsgArea [AREA <Area Number>] <MASKIN|MASKOUT|TOGGLE> [SIG] [ALL]

   FUNCTION

   INPUTS

   RESULT

   RC
                 0 -- Message masked
                 2 -- Message areas 
                10 -- Bad arguments
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node "ScanTopics"
@toc Msg
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
                ScanTopics -- Retreives information about threads in a message area.

   SYNOPSIS
                ScanTopics [AREA <Area Number>]

   FUNCTION

   INPUTS

   RESULT

   RC
                 0 -- Message area scanned
                 5 -- Could not scan message area
                10 -- Bad arguments
                20 -- Fatal error

   EXAMPLE

