; ##############################################################################
; ##############################################################################
; ##############################################################################
; ########                                                              ########
; ########                Zeus/Door/IO AREXX Commands                   ########
; ########                                                              ########
; ##############################################################################
; ##############################################################################
; ##############################################################################

@node ABBEREXX
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME

       CliDoor '"Abberexx"' -- Runs an Abberexx door.

   SYNOPSIS

       CliDoor '"Abberexx 'LINE/A' TYPE/K DOOR/A/F"'

   FUNCTION

       This is an interface to run Abberexx doors. This isn't
       actually an ARexx command, the interface for Abberexx
       is external to Zeus. It's included in the documentation
       for completeness since Abberexx is widely used.

   INPUTS

       Line    -    Using the standard Zeus scripts, simply pass
                    this as Line. In Zeus, line is filled with
                    the line the command was executed from.

       Type    -    Since there are some different type of
                    Abberexx interfaces in other BBS's, this
                    allows you to set the subtle differences
                    necessary for them.

                    Type=CNET  for CNet doors.
                    Type=XLK   for XenoLink doors.

                    or don't include Type for standard Abberexx.

   RESULT

   RC

   EXAMPLE

       CLIDoor '"ABBERexx 'Line' TYPE=CNET EL.PD"'

       CLIDoor '"ABBERexx 'Line' TYPE=XLK Assassin/Assassin.trans 'Line'"'

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node ADDUSERXDATA
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       AddUserXData -- Add/Replace an item of extra data.

   SYNOPSIS
       AddUserXData <Type> <Data> [User]

   FUNCTION
       Each user has a database of information which can be added to using
       this function.  Each item of information has a four character tag
       associated with it.  If the tag you specify already exists in the
       database the data will be replaced.

   INPUTS
       Type - Four character tag of the item you wish to add.  This is
              case sensitive.
       Data - The data to store.
       User - Optional user pointer.  If not supplied, the user currently
              online will be affected.

   RC
       0 - Data added/replaced.
      10 - Bad args. 
      20 - Illegal user pointer/no user online

   NOTES
      Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO
      @{"LoadUserXData" Link "LoadUserXData"}, @{"GetUserXData" Link "GetUserXData"}      

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node ASYNCREXX
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       AsyncRexx -- Starts an external rexx script.

   SYNOPSIS
       AsyncRexx '<ScriptName> [Arguments]'

   FUNCTION
       Spawns a new task which in turn starts the given script.  Control
       returns to the Zeus rexx script immediately.

   NOTES
       This command is not for spawning Zeus scripts, it is for scripts
       which communicate with other programs, and do not directly need to
       output to an online user.
       
   INPUTS
       ScriptName - Name of the script to call.  The script will be started
                    as a 'normal' rexx script.  I.e. it should reside in
                    Rexx: and have a normal .rexx extension (if one is not
                    specified). A script can be stored anywhere if a
                    path is given.

    RC
       0 - Task created (no indication of whether the script was started
           successfully).
       5 - Task could not be started (out of memory etc).

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CALLSCRIPT
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       CallScript -- Runs a subscript.

   SYNOPSIS
       CallScript '<ScriptName>'

   FUNCTION
       CallScript allows you to call scripts without exiting the current
       script.  It's main use is for subscripts like 'WriteMsg', where
       after completion you want drop back to the exact place you called
       it in the main messages menu.

   NOTES
       You shouldn't use 'NextScript' or 'LastScript' inside the called
       script as this will actually set the next script for the calling
       script!
       
   INPUTS
       ScriptName - Name of the script to call.  Should be without path
                    or '.zeus' extension so Zeus can perform file name
                    checking correctly.

    RC
       10            - No script name given.
       20            - Out of memory.
       Anything else - Return code from script.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CHECKALIAS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       CheckAlias -- Check to see if an alias is already being used.

   SYNOPSIS
       CheckAlias '"<Alias>"'

   FUNCTION
       This function checks whether the given alias is being used by anyone
       else.  It checks the name and alias fields of all other users.
       
   INPUTS
       Alias - The alias to check.

    RC
       0 - Alias is not being used.
       5 - Alias is already being used.
      10 - Bad arguments.

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CHECKINPUT
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       CheckInput -- See if the user has pressed a key.

   SYNOPSIS
       CheckInput

   FUNCTION
       During a looping script (scanning messages or listing areas) you can
       use CheckInput to find out if the user has pressed a key, and abort
       the loop.

   INPUTS
       None.

   RC
       0 - User has not pressed a key
       5 - User has pressed a key

   RESULT
       None.

   EXAMPLE

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CHKCARRIER
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ChkCarrier - Check the carrier status

   SYNOPSIS
       ChkCarrier

   FUNCTION
       ChkCarrier can be used to detect whether a user is still online,
       and as such should be called at the start of scripts which
       require that a user be online when called.

   RC
       0 - Carrier present
       5 - No carrier present

   NOTES
       Will always return zero for a local line

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CHKLINEACCESS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ChkLineAccess - Checks the lines access settings

   SYNOPSIS
       ChkLineAccess [User]

   FUNCTION
       This function is only useful on non-local lines.  If you have setup
       access restrictions on a line, this function can be used to find out
       if a user can logon or not.  Typically this will be called immediatly
       after a user has successfully logged on.

   NOTES
       Users who have the UF_NORESTRICT flag set will cause this function
       to ALWAYS return zero.
       
   INPUTS
       User - Optional user as obtained from LOADUSER call.  If not
              provided, the user currently online will be used.

   RC
       0 - User may logon
       1 - No-one may logon now
       2 - Baud rate is not high enough
       3 - Baud rate is too high
       4 - Users access is not high enough
       5 - Users access is too high

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  |  Line Number 

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CHKUSERSTATS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ChkUserStats -- Checks the access of a given user.

   SYNOPSIS
       ChkUserStats [User]

   FUNCTION
       Checks the access of a given user, or if no User argument is given,
       the user online.  Generally used in a Logon script only, to validate
       that a calling user may access the BBS.

   INPUTS
       User - Optional user as obtained from LOADUSER call.  If not
              provided, the user currently online will be used.

   RESULT

   RC
       0 - User okay, and may access the BBS
       1 - Unknown user
       2 - User has reached the maximum calls they may make per day
       3 - User has used all their alloted daily time
       4 - User has been banned
       5 - User account has expired
       6 - User is already logged on to another line

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       Users who have the UF_NORESTRICT flag set will cause this function
       to ALWAYS return zero.

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CLEARHISTORY
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ClearHistory -- Clears the command line history of a line.

   SYNOPSIS
       ClearHistory

   FUNCTION
       Clears the command line history.  After calling, any Read
       commands which have History enabled will have no commands
       in that history.

   INPUTS

   RESULT

   RC
       0 - Always successful.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       Especially useful for conference-style BBS menus.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"Read 'USEHIST'" link "Read"} @{"Write" link "Write"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CLEARSCRIPT
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ClearScript -- Clears the script set by NextScript.

   SYNOPSIS
       ClearScript

   FUNCTION
       If you need to exit from a script and want it to be called again but
       you have already called 'NextScript' then 'ClearScript' will reset
       the NextScript field of the line.

   NOTES
       
   INPUTS

   RC
       0 - Always successful.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"NextScript" link "NextScript"} @{"KillScript" link "KillScript"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CLIDOOR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       CLIDoor - Run an AmigaDOS program

   SYNOPSIS
       CLIDoor '"<[Path:]Program> [Arguments]"' [BREAKD] [CTRLC] [CTRLD]
          [DIR <Directory>] [EXPAND] [MORE] [NOLOG] [NORESET] [PASSC]
          [PASSD] [RAW] [STACK <Stack Size>]

   FUNCTION
       Runs a normal CLI based program and redirects the input and output
       through Zeus to the user.

   INPUTS
       Program   - The AmigaDOS name of the executable.
       Arguments - These will be passed to the door and may contain
                   control codes.

       BREAKD    - If Zeus needs to break the door it will send a ^D
                   instead of a ^C.
       CTRLC     - When the user presses ^C the door receives a ^C signal.
       CTRLD     - When the user presses ^D the door receives a ^D signal.
       DIR       - The directory to start the program in.
       EXPAND    - If the door writes Zeus control codes, they will be
                   expanded.
       MORE      - Zeus will still bring up 'Press RETURN to continue'
                   messages in the door.
       NOLOG     - Nothing will be written to the Line-x.Log file.
       NORESET   - Zeus will not send the RIP reset commands before
                   entering the door.
       PASSC     - ^C is sent to the door as a normal character not a
                   signal to the program.
       PASSD     - ^D is sent to the door as a normal character.
       RAW       - Makes the door run in raw mode.
       STACK     - Sets the stack size of the program.

   RC
       RC is the result code of the door run.

   NOTES

       All programs are started, by default, from the DOORS:
       directory so 'DOORS:Game/Game' will work just like
       'Game/Game'.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CLOSEDEV
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       CloseDev - Close the serial device down on a line.

   SYNOPSIS
       CloseDev

   FUNCTION
       This function can be useful if you want to run a program that does
       not opens the serial device in shared mode.

   NOTES
       It is safe to call this function for local lines and when the device
       has previously been closed.

   SEE ALSO

       @{"OpenDev" link OpenDev}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CLRSCR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ClrScr - Clears the screen.

   SYNOPSIS
       ClrScr [FORCE]

   FUNCTION
       Clears the users screen if they have enabled clearing codes (See
       SetUserFlag).  This can be overidden by using the FORCE argument.

   INPUTS
       FORCE -- Forces a screen clear even if the user doesn't want them.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node CLRUSERFLAG
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ClrUserFlag -- Clears one of the current users flags.

   SYNOPSIS
       ClrUserFlag [MORE] [EXPERT] [HOTKEYS] [NO8BIT] [VALIDATED] [CLRSCR]
                   [LOGUSER] [NOANSI] [CRLF]

   FUNCTION
       Clears the specified user flag.
       
   INPUTS
       MORE      - Does the user want More? prompts.
       EXPERT    - Is the user in expert mode.
       HOTKEYS   - Does the user want hot keys.
       NO8BIT    - Does the user want only 7 bit characters
       VALIDATED - Is the user validated.
       CLRSCR    - Does the user want screen clears to be sent.
       LOGUSER   - Log this users activities.
       NOANSI    - Does the user want no ANSI codes to be sent.
       CRLF      - Does the user want CR/LF instead of just CR

    RC
       0 - Flag was cleared.
      10 - No user online or bad arguments.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node DELVAR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       DelVar -- Deletes an environmental variable.

   SYNOPSIS
       DelVar <Name> [GLOBAL]

   FUNCTION
       Deletes the variable.

   INPUTS
       Name   - The name of the variable to delete.
       GLOBAL - If this flag is given, only global variables (those visable
                to all programs running on the computer) will looked at.

   RC
       0 - Variable was deleted.
       5 - Error deleting variable.
      10 - Bad arguments.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node DETECTANSI
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       DetectANSI -- Find out if the users terminal supports ANSI codes.

   SYNOPSIS
       DetectANSI

   FUNCTION
       Asks the users terminal for a cursor position report.  If it gets a
       reply in 0.25 seconds, the function returns TRUE.

   RC
       0 - Terminal supports ANSI.
       5 - Terminal doesn't support ANSI.

   NOTES
       Some terminals support most ANSI codes but don't support this
       interactive code.  In this case, rely on the user's terminal
       settings

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node DETECTIEMSI
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       DetectIEMSI -- Detect IEMSI from user.

   SYNOPSIS
       DetectIEMSI

   FUNCTION
       After calling StartIEMSI, the users terminal will send it's IEMSI
       information about who the user is (if it can do IEMSI).  DetectIEMSI
       detects this information and completes the IEMSI handshake.

   RC
       0 - No IEMSI capabilities or IEMSI error.
       5 - IEMSI detected and handshake was successful.

   RESULT
       If IEMSI has been successful, RESULT will contain the name of the
       user who is calling.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"StartIEMSI" link StartIEMSI}, @{"GetIEMSIInfo" link GetIEMSIInfo}, @{"SetIEMSIOpts" link SetIEMSIOpts}, Scripts:Logon/Logon.zeus

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node DETECTRIP
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       DetectRIP -- Find out if the users terminal supports RIP codes.

   SYNOPSIS
       DetectRIP

   FUNCTION
       Asks the users terminal for it's RIP version string.  If it gets a
       reply in 0.25 seconds, the function returns TRUE.

       On local lines DetectRIP will return 0 if the Zeus RIP server is
       running, 5 if not.

   RC
       0 - Terminal supports RIP.
       5 - Terminal doesn't support RIP.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node DISABLERIP
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       DisableRIP -- Rexx macro for disabling RIP graphics.

   SYNOPSIS
       DisableRIP

   FUNCTION
       Sends the ANSI code to the users terminal instructing it to start
       processing RIP strings as plain text.

   NOTES
       Nothing is sent if RIP has not been detected or the user doesn't
       want RIP graphics.
       
   INPUTS
       None.

   RC
       0 - ANSI code sent.
      10 - User did not have RIP enabled.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"EnableRIP" link "EnableRIP"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node DISPLAY
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       Display - Display a text file

   SYNOPSIS
       Display '<Filename>' [BREAK] [FORCE] [ISMENU] [NOBUFFER] [NOCOOK]
                            [NOEXPAND] [NOMORE] [NORESET]

   FUNCTION
       Display will send an entire text file to the user.  Several flags
       are available to affect the output.  By default the text file will
       be buffered and if the output fills the users display, a More? Y/N/C
       prompt will be used.  If the user has RIP graphics enabled, their
       terminal will be reset.

   INPUTS
       Filename - the name of the file to send.  See the file
                  'Text-System.doc' for furthur information.

       BREAK    - If the user presses a key while the file is displaying,
                  DISPLAY will stop and return.
       FORCE    - If the output fills the users display, they will see a
                  'Press RETURN to continue' prompt and not be given a
                  chance to abort the output.
       ISMENU   - The file will not be displayed if the user has Expert
                  mode turned on.
       NOBUFFER - This text file will not be buffered by Zeus.  Useful for
                  lists of last callers and other files which change
                  regularly.
       NOCOOK   - Zeus will not strip ANSI codes, Clear Screen codes or
                  perform 8 bit character translation, even if the users
                  settings want this.  The file will be to the user
                  verbatim.  Use of this flag is not recommended.
       NOEXPAND - Control codes in the file will not be expanded.
       NOMORE   - No "More?" prompts will appear if the output fills the
                  users screen.
       NORESET  - Do not reset the users terminal if they have RIP graphics
                  enabled.

   RC
        Same as Write:

        2 -- User answered continuous to a USEMOREYNC prompt.
        1 -- Text displayed to the user.
        0 -- No text was given to display.
       -2 -- User stopped input by pressing a key (BREAK option).
       -3 -- The error returned from the SPECIALMORE option.
       -4 -- Carrier lost while text was displaying.
       -5 -- User answered NO to a more? prompt.

   SEE ALSO

       @{"Write" link Write}
       
@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node DISPLAYBLTN
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       DisplayBltn -- Displays a bulletin

   SYNOPSIS
       DisplayBltn '<Number>'

   FUNCTION
       Displays the bulletin with the given number to the user
       online.

   INPUTS
       Number - Number of the bulletin to display.

   RESULT
       None.
   
   RC
       0 - Success.
       5 - Error.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node DOESUSEREXIST
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       DoesUserExist -- Finds out if a user exists.

   SYNOPSIS
       DoesUserExist '"'<User Name>'"'

   FUNCTION
       Checks if the user has called before and their record has been
       saved.
       
   INPUTS
       UserName - May be a users name or their alias.

    RC
       0 - User exists.
       5 - User does not exist.
      10 - Bad args - user name not given.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node DRAWBAR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       DrawBar -- Rexx macro to draw a coloured background bar for text
                  input.

   SYNOPSIS
       DrawBar <Length> [Background Colour] [Foreground Colour]

   FUNCTION
       Draws a series of coloured spaces to enhance text entry.  The cursor
       is put back to the beginning of the bar after it is drawn.

   NOTES
       If ANSI has not been detected or the user has selected 'NO ANSI'
       then nothing will happen.
       
       If either Foreground or Background colours are not specified it is
       assumed they have already been set and no ANSI colour codes will be
       generated.
       
   INPUTS
       Length      -- The length of the bar to draw.
       Back Colour -- The colour of the bar. (Range: 0 to 7)
       Fore Colour -- The text colour.       (Range: 0 to 7 or 10 to 17)

   RC
       0 - Drew bar (if user had ANSI enabled)
      10 - Illegal inputs.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node ENABLERIP
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       EnableRIP -- Rexx macro for enabling RIP graphics.

   SYNOPSIS
       EnableRIP

   FUNCTION
       Sends the ANSI code to the users terminal instructing it to start
       processing RIP strings again (after a DisableRIP call).

   NOTES
       Nothing is sent if RIP has not been detected or the user doesn't
       want RIP graphics.
       
   INPUTS
       None.

   RC
       0 - ANSI code sent.
      10 - User did not have RIP enabled.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"DisableRIP" link "DisableRIP"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node ENDUSERKEY
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       EndUserKey -- Frees up a userkey.

   SYNOPSIS
       EndUserKey <UserKey>

   FUNCTION
       Cleans up and deallocates the given userkey.
       
   INPUTS
       UserKey - Pointer to a userkey as generated by InitUserKey.

   RC
        0 - Success.
       10 - Bad arguments.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"InitUserKey" link "InitUserKey"} @{"UserFromKey" link "UserFromKey"} @{"GetKeyAlias" link "GetKeyAlias"} @{"NextUserKey" link "NextUserKey"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node ERRORLOG
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ErrorLog -- Writes to the error log file.

   SYNOPSIS
       ErrorLog <Type> '"<Data>"'

   FUNCTION
       Writes the given data to the error log file including date and time
       information.  The Type should be one character which will go at the
       start of the line.

   INPUTS
       Type - A single ID character, written at the start of log line.
       Data - The data to be written to the log.

   RC
       0 - No problems.
      10 - Bad arguments.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node EXPANDCC
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ExpandCC -- Expand a control code within rexx.

   SYNOPSIS
       ExpandCC '"<Control Code>"'

   FUNCTION
       ExpandCC expands the given control code and returns it in RESULT.
       
   INPUTS
       ControlCode - A control code, see CC docs for format information.

    RC
        0 - Success.
        5 - Unknown control code.
       10 - Bad arguments.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  |  Line Number 

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node FLUSHINPUT
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       FlushInput -- Clears the input stream of the current line.

   SYNOPSIS
       FlushInput

   FUNCTION
       'Eats' any input that may be waiting in the lines input stream.
       For example, if a large text has just been shown, and the user
       hit a key while it was being displayed, then this key would
       normally be sent to the next menu displayed.  This command
       can stop this happening.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node FORCE8BIT
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       Force8Bit -- Switches line to 8 bit mode.

   SYNOPSIS
       Force8Bit

   FUNCTION
       Sets the current line to 8 bit mode whether or not the
       current user's preferences are set for it.

   INPUTS

   RESULT

   RC
       0 -- Always successful.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       8 bit ANSI includes the high ASCII characters, which can
       be graphics characters or symbols such as: Ł, ö, ď, ő, é.

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETALIASFROMNAME
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetAliasFromName -- Returns an alias from a name.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetAliasFromName '"<UserName>"'

   FUNCTION
       Gets a user's alias from their real name.

   INPUTS
       UserName -- A user's real name

   RESULT
       User's Alias

   RC
        0 -- Successful.  RESULT contains alias.
        5 -- Unknown user
       10 -- Bad arguments

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO
       @{"GetNameFromAlias" link "GetNameFromAlias"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETGLOBALCMD
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetGlobalCmd -- Gets the command associated with a key.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetGlobalCmd '"'<Key>'"'

   FUNCTION
       If the specified key is defined in the global menu command list then
       the commands will be returned in RESULT which can then be
       interpreted.  This makes your scripts smaller thus speeding up menu
       loading. Global commands are stored in Zeus:Config/Zeus/GlobalCmds.cfg
       and take the form of:

       #<key>
       <arexx code>

       Eg.:

       #*
       getuserdata 'ACCESS'
       if result > 199 then do
          nextscript 'SysOp/SysOpMenu'
          exit
       end
       signal MENULOOP
       
   INPUTS
       Key - One or more characters read from the user.

   RC
       0 - Success.
       5 - Key not defined.
      10 - No key given.

   RESULT
       If RC = 0 then RESULT contains the instruction(s) to interpret.

   EXAMPLE

       /* Script snippet from a MenuLoop */

       do forever
          ShowEvents

          Write '"Main Menu - Enter command: "'
          Read IsMenu
          if RC ~= 0 then exit
          CmdString = RESULT
       
          GetGlobalCmd '"'CmdString'"'
          if RC = 0 then
             Interpret RESULT
          else do
             Cmd = 'Signal Option_'CmdString
             Interpret Cmd
             end
          
          end

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETIEMSIINFO
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetIEMSIInfo -- Get some information from the IEMSI data.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetIEMSIInfo <Type>

   FUNCTION
       If IEMSI was successful, Zeus saves all the IEMSI data from the
       user which can then be accessed by GetIEMSIInfo.

   INPUTS
       Type - One of the following keywords:

             NAME      - Users name.
             ALIAS     - Users alias.
             LOCATION  - Users location.
             DATANUM   - Data phone number.
             VOICENUM  - Voice phone number.
             PASSWORD  - Password.
             BIRTHDATE - Birthdate (seconds from Jan 1st 1970).
             CRTDEF    - Terminal settings.
             PROTOCOLS - Supported protocols.
             CAPABS    - Terminal capabilities.
             REQUESTS  - What the user wants to do.
             SOFTWARE  - What software the user is using.

   RC
       0 - RESULT contains data requested.
       5 - Type not recognised.
      10 - Type not given.
      20 - User did not use IEMSI to logon.

   RESULT
       The data asked for.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"StartIEMSI" link "StartIEMSI"} @{"DetectIEMSI" link "DetectIEMSI"} @{"SetIEMSIOpts" link "SetIEMSIOpts"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETKEYALIAS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetKeyAlias -- Gets the alias from a userkey.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetKeyAlias <UserKey>

   FUNCTION
       Returns the alias held in the given userkey.
       
   INPUTS
       UserKey - Pointer to a userkey as generated by InitUserKey.

   RC
       0 - Success.
      10 - Bad arguments.

   RESULT
       Contains the alias from the key.

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO
       @{"InitUserKey" link "InitUserKey"} @{"UserFromKey" link "UserFromKey"} @{"NextUserKey" link "NextUserKey"} @{"EndUserKey" link "EndUserKey"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETKEYNAME
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetKeyName -- Gets the name from a userkey.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetKeyName <UserKey>

   FUNCTION
       Returns the name held in the given userkey.
       
   INPUTS
       UserKey - Pointer to a userkey as generated by InitUserKey.

   RC
       0 - Success.
      10 - Bad arguments.

   RESULT
       Contains the name from the key.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO
       @{"InitUserKey" link "InitUserKey"} @{"UserFromKey" link "UserFromKey"} @{"GetKeyAlias" link "GetKeyAlias"} @{"NextUserKey" link "NextUserKey"} @{"EndUserKey" link "EndUserKey"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETLANGSTR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetLangStr -- Returns a Language string.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetLangStr '<Identifier>' [LanguageNumber]

   FUNCTION
       Gets a string from the Language files using the identifier
       provided.

   INPUTS
       Identifier -- The string to find in the language files.

       LanguageNumber -- If provided, the Identifier if looked up
                         in the language file corresponding to this
                         number.

   RESULT
       The string requested.

   RC
        0 -- Successful
       10 -- Bad args or string not found.

   EXAMPLE

                GetFile 'Entry' '"'File'"' 'Uploaded'
                FUploaded   = RESULT
                GetLangStr 'TIME'
                Strftime FUploaded '"'RESULT'"'
                FUploaded   = RESULT

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETLOGOFFCODE
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetLogOffCode -- Finds out how a user logged off.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetLogOffCode [User]

   FUNCTION
       Find out why/how the user logged off.  If no user argument
       is provided the last online user of the current line is
       used.

   INPUTS
       User -- optionally a user as loaded with LoadUser.

   RESULT
       Log off code:

        1 -- Inactivity loggout. The user has not pressed a key for the specified
             amount of idle time set in the Zeus configuration.

        2 -- Forced logout. (SysOp booted user).
        3 -- User dropped carrier (connection lost).
        4 -- User ran out of online time for the current call.

   RC
        0 -- Successful; code in RESULT
       10 -- Bad arguments

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

       You should use this in your Zeus:Scripts/BootUser.zeus script as Zeus
       will execute that script each time a user is logged off.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"ChkLineAccess" link "ChkLineAccess"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETNAMEFROMALIAS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetNameFromAlias -- Returns a name based on a user alias.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetNameFromAlias '"<Alias>"'

   FUNCTION
       Gets a user's real name from their alias.

   INPUTS
       Alias -- A user's alias

   RESULT
       User's real name

   RC
        0 -- Successful.  RESULT contains name.
        5 -- Unknown user
       10 -- Bad arguments

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous

   SEE ALSO
       @{"GetAliasFromName" link "GetAliasFromName"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETSTATUS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetStatus -- Gets the status of a line.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetStatus [LineNumber]

   FUNCTION
       Gets the status string associated with the given line number.  If no
       number is specified then the current lines string is returned.

   INPUTS
       LineNumber - Which line to get the data from.

   RC
       0 - Got the data.
      10 - Specified line doesn't exist.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  |  Line Number 

   SEE ALSO
       @{"SetStatus" link "SetStatus"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETSYSVAR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetSysVar -- Gets a System variable.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetSysVar <UserIdxBuff|CarChkInterval|InAcTime|SystemName|
                                      SystemLocation|SysopName>

   FUNCTION
       Returns the value of one of the global system variables set
       usually in the Prefs/System program.  These reflect certain
       configurable aspects of the BBS's behaviour.

   INPUTS
       USERIDXBUFF    -- The buffer (memory size) used by Zeus to store user
                         Indexes.

       CARCHKINTERVAL -- The interval Zeus uses to check for a carrier. (To see if
                         the user is still online).

       INACTIME       -- The amount of time a user can not hit a key before being
                         inactively logged off.

       SYSTEMNAME     -- The name of the BBS.
       SYSTEMLOCATION -- The location of the BBS.
       SYSOPNAME      -- The name of the SysOp.

   RESULT
       Data requested.

   RC
        0 -- Successful.
       20 -- Error (Bad args).

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETUSERDATA
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetUserData -- Get some data from the user currently online.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetUserData <Type>

   FUNCTION
       If RC equals NULL then RESULT will contain the data asked for.  An
       error indicates that there is no user online.
       
   INPUTS
       Type - can be one of:
              NAME           - The users name.
              ALIAS          - Their alias.
              PASSWORD       - Their password.
              VOICEPHONE     - Their voice phone number.
              DATAPHONE      - Their data phone number.
              STREET         - Their street address.
              TOWN           - Their town.
              CITY           - (Same as TOWN)
              COUNTY         - Their county.
              STATE          - (Same as COUNTY)
              POSTCODE       - Their postcode.
              ZIPCODE        - (Same as POSTCODE)
              COUNTRY        - Their country.
              FIRSTCALL      - Their first call in the format:
                                'DD-MMM-YY HH:MM:SS'
              LASTCALL       - Their last call in the format:
                                'DD-MMM-YY HH:MM:SS'
              LASTBAUD       - The baudrate of their last call.
              MINSLEFT       - Number of minutes left this call.
              NUMCALLS       - Number of calls they have made to this BBS.
              ACCESS         - Their access level.
              MAXCALLSPERDAY - Their max calls per day limit.
              MAXMINSPERCALL - Their max minutes per call limit.
              MAXMINSPERDAY  - Their max minutes per day limit.
              COMPUTER       - Their computer type.
              SCRWIDTH       - Their screen width.
              SCRHEIGHT      - Their screen height.
              MENUSET        - Their menu set.
              LANGUAGE       - Their language.
              CALLSTODAY     - Number of connects they have had today.

   RESULT
       The type of data asked for.
   
   RC
        0 - Got data ok.
       >0 - No user present.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

   SEE ALSO
       @{"SetUserData" link "SetUserData"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETUSERFLAG
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetUserFlag -- Get the status of one of the users flags.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetUserFlag [MORE] [EXPERT] [HOTKEYS] [NO8BIT] [VALIDATED] [CLRSCR]
                   [LOGUSER] [NOANSI] [CRLF]

   FUNCTION
       Returns whether one of the users flags is set.
       
   INPUTS
       MORE      - Does the user want More? prompts.
       EXPERT    - Is the user in expert mode.
       HOTKEYS   - Does the user want hot keys.
       NO8BIT    - Does the user want only 7 bit characters
       VALIDATED - Is the user validated.
       CLRSCR    - Does the user want screen clears to be sent.
       LOGUSER   - Log this users activities.
       NOANSI    - Does the user want no ANSI codes to be sent.
       CRLF      - Does the user want CR/LF instead of just CR

    RC
        0 - Flag is not set.
        1 - Flag is set.
       10 - No user online or bad arguments.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO
       @{"SetUserFlag" link "SetUserFlag"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETUSERXDATA
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetUserXData -- Gets an item of extra data.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetUserXData <Type> [User]

   FUNCTION
       If the users database contains an item of data that corresponds with
       the tag 'Type' it will be returned in RESULT.

   INPUTS
       Type - Four character tag of the item you wish to add.  This is
                 case sensitive.
       User - Optional user pointer.  If not supplied, the user currently
                 online will be referenced.

   RC
        0 - Data returned.
       10 - Bad args.
       20 - Illegal user pointer/no user online.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

   SEE ALSO
       @{"SetUserXData" link "SetUserXData"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETVAR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetVar -- Gets the contents of an environmental variable.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetVar <Name> [GLOBAL]

   FUNCTION
       Gets the data held within the named env variable.

   INPUTS
       Name   - The name of the variable to get.
       GLOBAL - If this flag is given, only global variables will looked
                at.

   RC
       0 - Variable was set.
       5 - Error setting variable.
      10 - Bad arguments.

   NOTES
       The maximum length of a variable is 256 characters

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

   SEE ALSO
       @{"SetVar" link "SetVar"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node GETYESNO
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       GetYesNo -- Prompts the user for a yes/no answer.

   SYNOPSIS
       GetYesNo <YES/NO>

   FUNCTION
       The function will prompt the user for a yes or no answer.  If the
       user presses return, the given alternative will be returned.

   INPUTS
       Either YES or NO
       
   RESULT
       Either 'Y' or 'N'
       
   RC
       0 - The user selected the same option as the argument given.
       5 - The user selected the opposite of the argument given.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

