@node SCREENTOFRONT
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ScreenToFront -- Brings public screen or watcher screen to front.

   SYNOPSIS
       ScreenToFront [Public Screen Name] [Line Number]

   FUNCTION
       Brings public screen or watcher screen to front. If no name
       or line number is given the the Watcher of the current line
       is brought to front.

   INPUTS
       Public Screen Name  --  Name of a screen to bring forward.
       Line Number         --  Number of a line to bring its watcher
                               screen forward.

   RESULT

   RC
       0 -- Successful
       5 -- Bad Args.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

       Line's Watcher (or other named screen) must be open to bring
       its screen forward.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"ScreenToBack" link "ScreenToBack"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SCREENTOBACK
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ScreenToBack -- Pushes public screen or watcher screen to back.

   SYNOPSIS
       ScreenToBack [Public Screen Name] [Line Number]

   FUNCTION
       Pushes a public screen or watcher screen to the back of all
       open screens. If no name or line number is given the the
       Watcher of the current line is sent to the back.

   INPUTS
       Public Screen Name  --  Name of a screen to push back.
       Line Number         --  Number of a line to push its watcher
                               screen back.

   RESULT

   RC
       0 -- Successful
       5 -- Bad Args.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

       Line's Watcher (or other named screen) must be open to push
       its screen back.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"ScreenToFront" link "ScreenToFront"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SENDLINEMSG
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SendLineMsg -- Send a message to a line.

   SYNOPSIS
       SendLineMsg <Line Number> '"<Message>"'

   FUNCTION
       Sends the given text to the line with the specified number.  If
       there is no user online, the message will be lost.

   INPUTS
       Line Number - The number of the line to send the message to.
       Message     - The message text.  Up to 1024 characters only.

   RESULT
       None.

   RC
        0 - Message sent successfully.
       10 - Error in sending message.

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SERINPUT
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SerInput

   SYNOPSIS
       SerInput [ON | OFF]

   FUNCTION
       Turn serial input on or off. Turning serial input off will
       disable input from the user. This is a Low Level command
       and should not in general be used.

   INPUTS
       ON  -- Turn serial input back on.
       OFF -- Turn serial input off.

   RESULT
       None.

   RC
       0 -- Always successful.

   EXAMPLE
       None.

   NOTE

       OFF is the only real argument this command takes. Specifying
       anything other than OFF will turn serial input back on.
       Might as well stick to ON/OFF arguments for simplicity.

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  |  Line Number

   SEE ALSO

       @{"SerRead" link "SerRead"} @{"SerWrite" link "SerWrite"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SERREAD
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SerRead

   SYNOPSIS
       SerRead [CHAR] [LINE] [NOWAIT] [TIMEOUT]

   FUNCTION
       Low level reading from the serial port.

   INPUTS
       CHAR    -- Read a single character from the serial input.
       LINE    -- Read a line of text from the serial input.
       NOWAIT  -- Do not wait for input if there is none waiting.
       TIMEOUT -- Time to wait for input in milli-seconds.

   RESULT

   RC
        0 -- Input read and stored in RESULT.
       10 -- Bad arguments.
       20 -- Fatal Error. (Device not open)

   EXAMPLE

   NOTE

   SEE ALSO
       @{"SerWrite" link "SerWrite"} @{"SerInput" link "SerInput"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SERWRITE
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SerWrite

   SYNOPSIS
       SerWrite '"<STRING>"'

   FUNCTION
       Send commands to the modem directly though the used serial
       device on the current line.  Low Level.

   INPUTS
       STRING -- The string (or commands) to send to the modem.

   RESULT

   RC
        0 -- Command sent.
       10 -- Serial device not open.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"SerRead" link "SerRead"} @{"SerInput" link "SerInput"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETACCLIMIT
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SetAccLimit -- Sets users time limit for this call.

   SYNOPSIS
       SetAccLimit

   FUNCTION
       If you have defined access restrictions for a line then this
       function is used to reduce the amount of time the current user may
       spend online.  Minutes taken away from the user will be added back
       once they have logged off.

       Therefore this must be called after the user has logged on, and it
       is recommended you react on RC=5 and display to the user a screen
       showing their new time online.

   NOTES
       Users who have the UF_NORESTRICT flag set will not be affected by
       this function.

   RC
       0 - Users time was not changed
       5 - Users time was reduced due to an impending event
      10 - No user online

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  |  Line Number 

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETDEFRIP
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SetDefRIP -- Sets the users RIP data.

   SYNOPSIS
       SetDefRIP

   FUNCTION
       Initialises a RIP terminal if one has been detected.

   RC
        0 -- Reset code sent.
       10 -- User does not have RIP enabled or was not detected at login.

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETIEMSIOPTS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SetIEMSIOpts -- Sets the users data as asked for in IEMSI session.

   SYNOPSIS
       SetIEMSIOpts

   FUNCTION
       After a successful IEMSI handshake, DetectIEMSI returns the users
       name.  After you have loaded the user you should call SetIEMSIOpts
       which will set/clear various flags in the users structure.  The
       options that are affected are:

       ANSI Codes
       8 Bit chars
       Hot Keys
       Clear Screen
       More Prompts

   RC
       0 - Everything went ok.
      10 - User did not use IEMSI to logon.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"StartIEMSI" link "StartIEMSI"} @{"DetectIEMSI" link "DetectIEMSI"} @{"GetIEMSIInfo" link "GetIEMSIInfo"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETMSFLAGS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

    NAME
        SetMSFlags -- Sets users flags from their menu set

    SYNOPSIS
        SetMSFlags

    FUNCTION
        This function will take the users menu set (as set with SetUserData
        'MenuSet' x) and sets/clears various flags in the user structure.

        The flags that are affected are:

        UF_WANTRIP   - User wants RIP graphics
        UF_AMIGAANSI - User is using an Amiga terminal
        UF_NO8BIT    - Convert 8 bit characters
        UF_NOANSI    - Strip ANSI codes

    RC
        0 - Everything went fine.
       10 - Users menu set hasn't been defined in Prefs/System
       20 - No user online

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETSCRDIR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SetScrDir

   SYNOPSIS
       SetScrDir '<PATH>'

   FUNCTION
       Set the script directory for the current line.  The change
       is temporary, does not affect other lines, and will be
       undone when the current user logs off.

   INPUTS
       PATH -- the new scripts directory.

   RESULT

   RC
       0 -- Successful.
       5 -- Path isn't valid.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETSTATUS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SetStatus -- Sets the lines status string.

   SYNOPSIS
       SetStatus '"<Status>"'

   FUNCTION
       Sets the lines status string so when other lines call GetLineStatus
       they can see what you are up to.  This is also the text show in
       Voyeur to the SysOp.

   INPUTS
       Status - A short description of the users current action.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETTRANS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SetTrans

   SYNOPSIS
       SetTrans [INPUT] [OUTPUT] [BOTH] [ON] [OFF] [TABLE <TAG>]
                [ENTRY <FROM> <TO>] [RESET] [SAVE]

   FUNCTION
       Set the user's translation table.

   INPUTS

       INPUT  -- Only translate input.
       OUTPUT -- Only translate output.
       BOTH   -- Translate both input and output.
       ON     -- Turn translation on.
       OFF    -- Turn translation off.
       TABLE  -- The TAG name for the translation table to use.
       ENTRY  -- Numbers from 0 - 255. The range of the table entries to use.
       RESET  -- Reset the user's translation table.
       SAVE   -- Save the user's translation table setttings in the UserXData.

   RESULT

   RC
        0 -- Translation table set.
       10 -- Bad Arguments.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTE
       Asynchronous  |  Line Number

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETUSERDATA
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SetUserData -- Modify the current users data.

   SYNOPSIS
       SetUserData <Type> '"<Data>"'

   FUNCTION
       Modifies the current users structure with the supplied data.

   INPUTS
       Type - can be one of:
              ALIAS          - Their alias.
              PASSWORD       - Their password.
              VOICEPHONE     - Their voice phone number.
              DATAPHONE      - Their data phone number.
              STREET         - Their street address.
              TOWN           - Their town.
              CITY           - (Same as TOWN)
              COUNTY         - Their county.
              STATE          - (Same as COUNTY)
              POSTCODE       - Their postcode.
              ZIPCODE        - (Same as POSTCODE)
              COUNTRY        - Their country.
              LASTBAUD       - The baudrate of their last call.
              MINSLEFT       - Number of minutes left this call.
              NUMCALLS       - Number of calls they have made to this BBS.
              ACCESS         - Their access level.
              MAXCALLSPERDAY - Their max calls per day limit.
              MAXMINSPERCALL - Their max minutes per call limit.
              MAXMINSPERDAY  - Their max minutes per day limit.
              COMPUTER       - Their computer type.
              SCRWIDTH       - Their screen width.
              SCRHEIGHT      - Their screen height.
              MENUSET        - Their menu set.
              LANGUAGE       - Their language.
              CALLSTODAY     - Number of connects they have had today.

   RC
       0 - Data was set.
      10 - No user online, Bad arguments.

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETUSERFLAG
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SetUserFlag -- Sets one of the current users flags.

   SYNOPSIS
       SetUserFlag [MORE] [EXPERT] [HOTKEYS] [NO8BIT] [VALIDATED] [CLRSCR]
                   [LOGUSER] [NOANSI] [CRLF]

   FUNCTION
       Sets the specified user flag.

   INPUTS
       MORE      - Does the user want More? prompts.
       EXPERT    - Is the user in expert mode.
       HOTKEYS   - Does the user want hot keys.
       NO8BIT    - Does the user want only 7 bit characters
       VALIDATED - Is the user validated.
       CLRSCR    - Does the user want screen clears to be sent.
       LOGUSER   - Log this users activities.
       NOANSI    - Does the user want no ANSI codes to be sent.
       CRLF      - Does the user want CR/LF instead of just CR

    RC
       0 - Flag was set.
      10 - No user online or bad arguments.

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SETVAR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SetVar -- Sets an environmental variable.

   SYNOPSIS
       SetVar <Name> '"<Data>"' [GLOBAL]

   FUNCTION
       Sets an env variable to be 'Data'.

   INPUTS
       Name   - The name of the variable to set.
       Data   - The data to set the variable to.
       GLOBAL - If this flag is given, the variable will be accessable by
                other lines as well as from the shell command 'GetEnv'

   RC
        0 - Variable was set.
        5 - Error setting variable.
       10 - Bad arguments.

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

       The maximum length of a variable is 256 characters

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SHOWEVENTS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ShowEvents -- Shows the users Event.log

   SYNOPSIS
       ShowEvents

   FUNCTION
       ShowEvents will display the users event log if it exists.  It will
       also display any messages sent to this line via SENDLINEMSG.

   RESULT

   RC
       0 - All messages read.
       5 - The user didn't read all the available messages.

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node STARTIEMSI
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       StartIEMSI -- Tells other system we can do IEMSI.

   SYNOPSIS
       StartIEMSI

   FUNCTION
       Sends a 'magic' string to the users terminal letting it know we can
       do IEMSI logons.  If the users terminal can, it will respond.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"DetectIEMSI" link "DetectIEMSI"} @{"GetIEMSIInfo" link "GetIEMSIInfo"} @{"SetIEMSIOpts" link "SetIEMSIOpts"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node STARTUP
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       StartUp -- Starts the scripts up again after a KillScript

   SYNOPSIS
       StartUp

   FUNCTION
       If you have called KillScript then StartUp will start the scripts
       moving again starting at the script specified when BBSLine was
       run.

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  |  Line Number 

   SEE ALSO
       @{"KillScript" link "KillScript"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SWRITE
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SWrite

   SYNOPSIS
       SWrite

   FUNCTION
       Low level serial command.

   INPUTS

   RESULT

   RC

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node SUBTIME
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       SubTime

   SYNOPSIS
       SubTime <ON|OFF>

   FUNCTION
       Disables or enables subtracting online time from the current
       user.  While this is on, the time allocated for the user for
       this call does not decrease, so they can stay online for a
       corrispondingly longer time when SubTime is re-enabled.

   INPUTS
       ON   -- re-enables time subtracting.
       OFF  -- disables time subtracing.

   RESULT

   RC
        0 -- Successful
       10 -- Wrong args

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode


@node TERMCAPS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       TermCaps -- Find out what the users terminal can do.

   SYNOPSIS
       TermCaps '<Type>'

   FUNCTION
       If you called DETECTANSI, DETECTRIP, DETECTZAPP or DETECTIEMSI at some point,
       then Zeus will set a flag in the line structure.  TermCaps is
       used to query these flags so you don't have to call DETECT#? again.

   INPUTS
       Type - One of:

              'DOESANSI'  -- Does the users terminal support ANSI
              'DOESRIP'   -- Does the users terminal support RIP
              'DOESIEMSI' -- Did the user log on via IEMSI
              'DOESZAPP'  -- Does the users terminal support ZAPP

   RESULT
       None.

   RC
        0 - Flag is not set.
        1 - Flag is set.
       10 - Unrecognised type.
       20 - No type specified.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"DetectANSI" link "DetectANSI"} @{"DetectRIP" link "DetectRIP"} @{"DetectEMSI" link "DetectEMSI"}  @{"DetectZAPP" link "DetectZAPP"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node UNICONIFY
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       Uniconify

   SYNOPSIS
       Uniconify

   FUNCTION
       Uniconifies all the watchers for the current line.

   INPUTS

   RESULT

   RC
       0 -- Always Successful.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       Asynchronous  |  Line Number

   SEE ALSO
       @{"Iconify" link "Iconify"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node UNLOADUSER
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       UnLoadUser

   SYNOPSIS
       UnLoadUser <KEY>

   FUNCTION
       Unload a user structure from memory.

   INPUTS
       KEY -- A pointer to a user key structure.

   RESULT

   RC
        0 -- User account unloaded.
       10 -- Bad Arguments / Unable to unload user.

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

   SEE ALSO
       @{"LoadUser" link "LoadUser"} @{"PutOnline" link "PutOnline"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node UNREADBLTNS
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       UnReadBltns -- Check if user has read all the bulletins.

   SYNOPSIS
       UnReadBltns

   FUNCTION
       If any bulletins have been created/updated since the users last
       call, this function will let you know.

   INPUTS
       None.

   RESULT
       None.

   RC
       0 - User has read all bulletins (or no user online).
       5 - There are unread bulletins.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node USERCREDIT
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       UserCredit -- Sets/Gets the users credit status

   SYNOPSIS
       UserCredit <Credit> [User Pointer]

   FUNCTION
       Modifies the users credit status by the amount given and returns the
       current credit value.  Credit may be positive or negative or zero if
       you just want the users current status.  If a user pointer is
       supplied, that user will be modified rather than the user currently
       online.

   INPUTS
       Credit - Amount of credit to add/subtract
       User   - User pointer obtained from LoadUser

   RC
       0 - No Errors and users current credit status returned in RESULT.
      20 - No user online or bad user pointer.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node USERFROMKEY
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       UserFromKey -- Loads the user from the given userkey.

   SYNOPSIS
       UserFromKey <UserKey>

   FUNCTION
       Returns a pointer to a user structure that can be given to
       PutOnline.

   INPUTS
       UserKey - Pointer to a userkey as generated by InitUserKey.

   RC
        0 - User was loaded.
       10 - Error loading user or Bad arguments.

   RESULT
       Contains the alias from the key.

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

   SEE ALSO
       @{"InitUserKey" link "InitUserKey"} @{"GetKeyAlias" link "GetKeyAlias"} @{"NextUserKey" link "NextUserKey"} @{"EndUserKey" link "EndUserKey"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node WAITRETURN
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       WaitReturn -- Waits for the user to press the return key.

   SYNOPSIS
       WaitReturn [CLEAR]

   FUNCTION
       WaitReturn first prints out the text defined by the
       current language and then waits for the user to press
       their return key. Will either use WAITRETURN or
       WAITRETURNANIM language strings, depending on the user's
       settings.

   INPUTS
       If CLEAR is specified then the return prompt will be deleted
       afterwards so output will continue without a break.

   RC
        0 - No problems.
       10 - Lost carrier while waiting.
       20 - 'Line' variable not set.

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node WHOSONLINE
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       WhosOnline

   SYNOPSIS
       WhosOnline [<LINE>]

   FUNCTION
       Returns the name of an online user.

   INPUTS
       Line  --  Return user's name for this line.
                 If not specified, returns the current line's user's name.

   RESULT

       When RC is 0  -- The User's name.
       When RC is 5  -- "No user online"
       When RC is 10 -- "Waiting for call"

   RC
        0 -- Command successful and the user's name stored in RESULT.
        5 -- Currently no user on that line.
       20 -- Line is waiting for a call.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
          Asynchronous  

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node WRITE
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       Write -- Writes some data to the current line.

   SYNOPSIS
       Write '"<Text>"' [BREAK] [ISMENU] [NOABORT] [NOCOOK] [NOMORE]
                       [RIPONLY] [SPECIALMORE] [TXTONLY] [USEMOREYNC]

   FUNCTION
       Write outputs <Text> to the user. <Text> is a string of text which
       may contain ANSI codes, RIP codes, ControlCodes and may be a maximum
       of 1024 characters long.

   INPUTS

       TEXT        -- The text to output to the user.

       BREAK       -- If the user hits a key while text is displaying, it will
                      stop and return to the normal flow of the script.

       ISMENU      -- The text will not be displayed if user has expert mode
                      turned on.

       NOABORT     -- If the user's screen height is filled by the output, they
                      will recieve a press return prompt instead of a more? prompt.

       NOCOOK      -- Zeus will not strip 8Bit chars, ANSI codes or screen clears
                      from the text.

       NOMORE      -- Do not pause with a More? prompt if the user's screen
                      height is filled by the text.

       RIPONLY     -- The text will only be displayed to users with RIP graphics
                      enabled.

       SPECIALMORE -- If the user's screen height is reached, no more prompts will
                      be displayed, instead an error will be set in RC.

       TXTONLY     -- Do not display to the user if RIP graphics is enabled.

       USEMOREYNC  -- If the user's terminal height is filled by the text, a
                      Yes/No/Continuous prompt will be displayed instead of a
                      More? [Yes/No] style prompt.


   RESULT

   RC
        2 -- User answered continuous to a USEMOREYNC prompt.
        1 -- Text displayed to the user.
        0 -- No text was given to display.
       -2 -- User stopped input by pressing a key (BREAK option).
       -3 -- The error returned from the SPECIALMORE option.
       -4 -- Carrier lost while text was displaying.
       -5 -- User answered NO to a more? prompt.

   EXAMPLE

   NOTES
       String formatting:

       Any number of these string control codes can be added anywhere within the
       displaying text to achieve a desired result.

       \a -- Flash the screen (DisplayBeep() on Watcher, ANSI beep for user).
       \\ -- Output a \ character.
       \n -- A line feed.
       \r -- A carriage return.
       \t -- A tab.
       \b -- A backspace.
       \" -- Output a " (quote).
       \f -- A screen clear.
       \v -- Move text up one line.

   SEE ALSO
       @{"Display" link Display} @{"Read" link "Read"}

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node WRITELOG
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       WriteLog -- Writes to the current lines log file.

   SYNOPSIS
       WriteLog <Type> '"<Data>"'

   FUNCTION
       Writes the given data to the current lines log file including date
       and time information.  The Type should be one character which will
       go at the start of the line.

   INPUTS
       Type - A single character.
       Data - The data to be written to the log.

   RC
       0 - No problems.
      10 - Bad arguments.

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node WRITEUSERLOG
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       WriteUserLog -- Write some text to a users Event.log

   SYNOPSIS
       WriteUserLog '"<User Name>"' '"<Message>"'

   FUNCTION
       If the user is online, this function will call SendLineMsg, else it
       will write the given message to the users event log.

       This should be used to send a user brief messages relating to BBS
       usage.  A good example for usage is recording failed log on
       attempts.

   INPUTS
       User Name - The name or alias of the user to send the message to.
       Message   - The message text.  Maybe up to 1024 characters.

   RESULT
       None.

   RC
        0 - Message sent successfully.
       20 - Error in sending message.

   NOTES
       Asynchronous

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node ZAPP
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ZAPP

   SYNOPSIS
       ZAPP <Utility> [WAIT]

   FUNCTION
       Launch a ZAPP utility, such as ZNFS.

   INPUTS
       Utility  -- the server to be run.  The commands will be
                   searched for in Zeus:Bin/Zapp/.
       Wait     -- if specified, ZAPP will stop line input/output
                   until the command has finished.  Otherwise,
                   it will be run in the background.

   RESULT

   RC
       0 -- Successful
       5 -- Command not found or ZAPP not running

   EXAMPLE

       ZAPP '"PlayPCM 'Line' Files:Music/PCM/geebrain.pcm"'
       ZAPP '"MountNFS 'Line' Files:Modules/ NET NetWork"'

   NOTES
       Asynchronous | Line Number

   SEE ALSO
       ZAPP Commands Documentation

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node ZDOOR
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ZDoor -- Starts a Zeus door.

   SYNOPSIS
       ZDoor '"<Door> [Arguments]"' [NORESET] [NOLOG]

   FUNCTION
       Starts a Zeus door.  These doors don't use stdio functions like
       printf() but *MUST* use the I/O routines in zeus.library.

   INPUTS
       NORESET   - Zeus will not send the RIP reset commands before
                   entering the door.
       NOLOG     - Nothing will be written to the Line-x.Log file.

   RC
      -1 - Failure to start door.

      Anything else is the return code from the door.

   NOTES
       Doors are started in the Doors: directory.

@rem </PRE>
@endnode

@node ZSHELL
@toc AlphaIndex
@rem <PRE>

   NAME
       ZShell -- Starts a real AmigaDOS shell on the current line.

   SYNOPSIS
       ZShell [MORE] [CTRLC] [CTRLD] [SCRIPT <Script Name>]

   FUNCTION
       ZShell puts the user on the current line into a REAL AmigaDOS
       shell.  It behaves as a real shell would do so be carefull who gets
       access to this command.

   INPUTS
       MORE   - Zeus will still print up 'Press Return' messages.
       CTRLC  - Allows ^C through.
       CTRLD  - Allows ^D through.
       SCRIPT - Specifies the shells startup script.  This could be the
                standard 'S:Shell-Startup'.

   RC
       0 - Shell ran ok.
       5 - Out of memory.

   NOTES
       *SECURITY* *RISK* : Ensure this is only available to
       SysOp level users.

   SEE ALSO

@rem </PRE>
@endnode


